  "why": "QATest explicitly enforces semantic-consistency and naturalness checks at each mutation step (e.g., ROUGE-1 quality check against the selected seed and a perplexity-based authenticity ranking), and it uses a seed-selection strategy to reduce over-mutating some seeds. These mechanisms constrain similarity and realism relative to the immediate/current seed and to the evolving seed distribution, but the paper does not enforce similarity relative to the original seed nor fix semantically critical content across iterations. Because mutants are fed back into the seed pool and re-used for further mutation, small per-step changes can accumulate; the framework mitigates but does not eliminate cumulative drift. This matches the “Medium” category: controls similarity/naturalness between successive mutation steps but does not guarantee preservation relative to the original seed across iterations.",
